node.text: NASA astronauts Shane Kimbrough and Megan McArthur, Akihiko Hoshide of JAXA, and Thomas Pesquet of ESA get together to answer your questions about life in space, astronaut training, and their upcoming mission launching next month.

node.title: Get to know the astronauts of NASA’s SpaceX Crew-2 mission!

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by NASA Johnson Space Center on August 26, 2021. May be an image of planet and text.

node.text:
Forty years ago, Voyager 2 made its closest approach to Saturn, taking these photos along the way. 🪐

The first photo is a false-color image of Saturn to highlight the bands in the planet’s atmosphere. The spacecraft took this photograph from 30 million miles away.

Look close! 👀 Saturn and three of its moons are visible in the second image. Moon Tethys is on top, with its shadow on the planet. Moons Dione and Rhea are seen below.

The third image was taken by Voyager 2 as it was departing the ringed planet and onto its next flyby in our solar system.

node.text:
NASA aircraft flying in formation ✈️ 

Thomas Parent pilots the WB-57 with NASA sensor equipment operator Mallory Yates (photographed). Tim Williams pilots the ER-2 alongside them.

The aircraft were flying at 55,000 feet over Arkansas in support of two NASA Airborne Science Campaigns designed to study our Earth called ACCLIP and DCOTSS. #NationalAviationDay

📸: NASA/Mallory Yates

node.text:
Axiom Mission 1, welcome to Houston.

Michael López-Alegría is pictured training at the Space Vehicle Mockup Facility at NASA’s Johnson Space Center in Houston for Axiom Mission 1 (Ax-1) to the @iss. Private astronauts of @Axiom.Space began learning about space station systems and procedures in preparation for their planned stay aboard the orbiting laboratory. The mission is scheduled for no earlier than January 2022.

For the Ax-1 mission, Axiom is proposing López-Alegría, Larry Connor, Mark Pathy, and Eytan Stibbe as prime crew members. These private astronauts will receive a standard official review by NASA and its international partners and undergo NASA medical qualification testing before being approved for flight. López-Alegría will serve as Axiom's mission commander with Peggy Whitson as his backup.

📸 : Axiom Space, Inc./Bill Stafford

node.text:
What do #Artemis astronauts and Olympic athletes have in common? Rigorous training to achieve inspiring feats in space & sports!

In honor of the #Olympics, NASA’s Human Research Program celebrates athletes who, like our astronauts, prepare for years in pursuit of their dreams.

Here’s NASA astronaut Jessica Watkins preparing to submerge for an underwater spacewalk training at the Neutral Buoyancy Laboratory at NASA's Johnson Space Center in Houston. Astronauts spend approximately 10 hours under water for every hour they spend on spacewalks.

node.text:
Photographs of our Moon, taken 50 years ago during various stages of the Apollo 15 mission.

Most were taken by Al Worden as he orbited the Moon while @nasaastronauts David Scott and James Irwin explored the surface.

Throughout the course of the mission, astronauts conducted several spacewalks, deployed science experiments, took samples, and conducted a press conference to show the public video of their mission.

What questions do you have about Apollo 15? Drop them in the comments!

#nasahistory #americanhistory #apollo15 #50thanniversary #OTD #astronaut #apollo #moon

node.text:
TWO spacewalk anniversaries today! 👩‍🚀

This #NationalMoonDay, it’s the 52nd anniversary of “one giant leap for mankind.” It was the day Neil Armstrong and Buzz Aldrin took the first spacewalk on the Moon! 🌖

Exactly 20 years ago in 2001, @nasaastronauts Michael Gernhardt and James Reilly took the first spacewalk out of the Quest Joint Airlock. The two had installed it to the @iss days prior.

node.text:
The astronauts of NASA’s @spacex Crew-3 mission. 

Raja Chari (@astro_raja) will serve as mission commander with Tom Marshburn as pilot. Both are @nasaastronauts. 

Matthias Maurer of the European Space Agency and Kayla Barron of NASA will serve as mission specialists for the mission. 

The four are scheduled to launch no earlier than Oct. 31 from @nasakennedy, and will arrive at the @iss shortly after.

node.text:
The final flight.

10 years ago today in NASA history, the space shuttle Atlantis launched four @nasaastronauts to the International Space Station (@ISS).

The 12-day STS-135 mission brought an end to the 30-year space shuttle program. Atlantis' flight was the last time a space shuttle would launch. 

"When a generation accomplishes a great thing, it's got a right to stand back and for just a moment admire and take pride in its work," said astronaut Christopher Ferguson. "As the ISS now enters the era of utilization, we'll never forget the role the space shuttle played in its creation. Like a proud parent, we anticipate great things to follow from the men and women who build, operate, and live there."

node.text:
The first sample of an asteroid called Ryugu has arrived!

NASA's Johnson Space Center in Houston received its first sample of asteroid Ryugu, which was returned to Earth last December by the Japan Aerospace Exploration Agency’s (JAXA) Hayabusa2 spacecraft.

Studying carbonaceous asteroids like Ryugu could help scientists better understand how the solar system formed.

This is one of the first samples to leave Japan for preliminary investigation. As deputy leader of the mineralogy-petrology subteam for the preliminary analysis effort, Mike Zolensky was one of the first scientists to examine the sample to determine its basic nature.

Alongside Zolensky, Jangmi Han from the Astromaterials Research and Exploration Science Division, and James Martinez of the Structural Engineering Division at NASA Johnson worked together to complete an investigation of the sample.

Sample analyses were performed in the Scanning Electron Microscopy Lab in Johnson’s Structural Engineering Division within five days. Zolensky is one of a hundred investigators worldwide to receive a sample from JAXA.

node.text:
#SpotTheSpacewalker. That pair of legs you see against the background of Earth belongs to NASA astronaut Shane Kimbrough! (@astro_kimbrough)

Kimbrough conducted a spacewalk with ESA astronaut Thomas Pesquet to install new roll-out solar panels to the @iss.

This was the view from the Mission Control Center in Houston 1 hour and 34 minutes into the spacewalk. The spacewalkers spent more than 6 hours in total outside of the space station on Friday. 

📸: NASA / Robert Markowitz

node.text:
Happy #nationalselfieday from the Expedition 65 crew aboard the @ISS! 

Thomas Pesquet took the first photo last week during the first spacewalk to install new solar arrays to the International Space Station.

Mark Vande Hei snapped the second photo during his 2018 mission. He was doing maintenance on the station's robotic arm.

Aki Hoshide of Japan took his space selfie back in 2012 before installing a camera onto Canadarm2 outside of the space station.

Thomas got astronauts Shane Kimbrough and Aki Hoshide in the frame while the trio were in the @SpaceX Crew Dragon vehicle named Endeavour.

Megan McArthur and Aki Hoshide pause for a selfie in the fourth photo while their crewmates participated in a downlink event.

Megan also took a cool selfie with her reflection shown in a floating water bubble in 2009 in the final photo.

@thom_astro @astro_kimbrough @astro.megan #selfie #space #spacestation

node.text:
What do you want to name the manikin launching to the Moon on NASA’s #Artemis I mission?

Before NASA launches with a human crew of astronauts, we’re sending a “Moonikin” mass simulator for the first launch. And we need your help choosing it’s name!

This bracket-style contest is now open! The choices are: ACE, Wargo, Delos, Duhart, Campos, Shackleton, Montgomery, and Rigel.

Check out our link in bio for the meaning behind the names and how you can vote for your favorite!
